<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="96" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Species identification confirmed by RSA, 2016</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="97" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="97" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">
Widely distributed through most of the Palaearctic region (
<bibRefCitation pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Alonso-Zarazaga 2011</bibRefCitation>
), this adventive species was recorded for the first time in North America in 
<pageBreakToken pageId="2" pageNumber="97" start="start">1994</pageBreakToken>
, in Pennsylvania (
<bibRefCitation author="Hoebeke, ER" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="10" pageNumber="105" pagination="151 - 161" title="Ischnopterapion (Chlorapion) virens (Herbst) (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea: Brentidae: Apioninae), a Palearctic clover pest new to North America: Recognition features, distribution, and bionomics." volume="102" year="2000">Hoebeke et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Until now, it was known to occur in Canada only in the Maritime Provinces (
<bibRefCitation author="Bousquet, Y" journalOrPublisher="Pensoft, Sofia" pageId="9" pageNumber="104" title="Checklist of Beetles of Canada and Alaska. Second edition." year="2013">Bousquet et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). It is considered a pest of clovers, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Trifolium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Trifolium" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Trifolium</taxonomicName>
L. spp. (
<taxonomicName family="Fabaceae" lsidName="" pageId="2" pageNumber="97" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
). It can be distinguished from the superficially similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Bokor, 1923" authorityName="Bokor" authorityYear="1923" class="Insecta" family="Brentidae" genus="Stenopterapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stenopterapion meliloti" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meliloti">Stenopterapion meliloti</taxonomicName>
Kirby, 1808, by its smaller size and the bluish colour of its pronotum and venter (black in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. meliloti" pageId="2" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="meliloti">S. meliloti</taxonomicName>
). As indicated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoebeke, ER" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="10" pageNumber="105" pagination="151 - 161" title="Ischnopterapion (Chlorapion) virens (Herbst) (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea: Brentidae: Apioninae), a Palearctic clover pest new to North America: Recognition features, distribution, and bionomics." volume="102" year="2000">Hoebeke et al. (2000)</bibRefCitation>
and by the label data provided hereafter, the flight season extends until late in the year.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
